{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048145,"nonce":"gFC9hqsjPkzEg9rGcX3gDUhY7Hc=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2024-03-22T13:02:56Z]\n\nFixed the proliferating dimensions by adding `out_axes` to the vmap:\n\nhttps://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/6d8df18802326c80052dd10c60f4dbefff848ca4/feedbax/train.py#L286\n\nNote that this solution doesn't actually mean that all models in an ensemble will have an identical intervention applied to them on each trial. Because `AbstractTask.get_train_trial_with_intervenor_params` is called from within `train_step`, distinct trial specs (with distinct intervenor parameters) will be generated and passed for each model replicate. \n\nInstead, we're essentially treating the _default_ parameters of an intervenor as invariant across model replicates. For that reason, maybe it would work to set the `params` field of `AbstractIntervenor` subclasses as `static=True`. I think this would automatically prevent arrays inside of this field from being broadcast during a vmap; we probably wouldn't need to explicitly do `isinstance(x, AbstractIntervenor)` checks when ensembling. However, the Equinox docs specifically mention that `static=True` should be rarely used instead of `filter`/`combine` ops, and I've avoided doing so here.\n\nThere may be some downstream annoyances related to this solution. For example, if the default intervenor params contain any arrays, then when we use `tree_take` to slice out a single model from an ensemble of models, it will be necessary to pass `is_leaf=lambda x: isinstance(x, AbstractIntervenor)`, or else `tree_take` will try to slice along the nonexistent ensemble dimension for those arrays.","files":null}]}